            <entry xml:id="entry_gælæxxa" xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>gælæxxa</orth></form>
                <usg><lang/></usg>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>бедняга</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>poor fellow</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <abv:exampleGrp>
                    <abv:example>
                        <quote>soʒæg gælæxxa</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>горький („горючий“) бедняга</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>bitter poor fellow</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Bes."/><biblScope>30</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Из <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>glaxa</w>
                        <gloss><q>бедняга</q></gloss></mentioned>. Связано ли с этим <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <note type="comment" xml:lang="ru">(волжские говоры) </note><note
                            type="comment" xml:lang="en">(Volga dialects) </note><w>галах</w>
                        <gloss><q>босяк</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>оборванец</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru"
                            >М. Горький. Коновалов. Собр. соч., т. 3, М., 1950, стр.
                            19</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">M. Gorky. Konovalov. Coll. cit.,
                            vol. 3, M., 1950, p. 19</biblScope></bibl>: „Вот теперь я, например,—
                    что такое? Босяк, галах, пьяница“; <bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">К. Федин.
                            Первые радости. Избр. произведения, М., 1947, стр.
                            317</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">K. Fedin. First joys. Fav.
                            works, M., 1947, p. 317</biblScope></bibl>: „… галахи будут в театр
                            приходить…“)?%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>526</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>glaxa</w>
                        <gloss><q>poor fellow</q></gloss></mentioned>. Is <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <note type="comment" xml:lang="ru">(волжские говоры) </note><note
                            type="comment" xml:lang="en">(Volga dialects) </note><w>galax</w>
                        <gloss><q>tramp</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>vagabond</q></gloss></mentioned> related to it (<bibl><biblScope
                            xml:lang="ru">М. Горький. Коновалов. Собр. соч., т. 3, М., 1950, стр.
                            19</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">M. Gorky. Konovalov. Coll. cit.,
                            vol. 3, M., 1950, p. 19</biblScope></bibl>: “Take me, for instance —
                    what am I? A tramp, a drunkard, a %igood-for-nothing%i [Russian
                        %iгалах%i].”;<note type="footnote" n="1"> PUT NOTE HERE </note>
                    <bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">К. Федин. Первые радости. Избр. произведения, М.,
                            1947, стр. 317</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">K. Fedin. First joys.
                            Fav. works, M., 1947, p. 317</biblScope></bibl>: “…poor fellows
                    [Russian %iгалахи%i] will come to the theater…”)?%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>526</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <note type="footnote" xml:lang="ru" n="1"/>
                <note type="footnote" xml:lang="en" n="1">Cited from: <bibl><author>M.
                            Gorky.</author><biblScope>Konovalov. Translated by Margaret Wettlin. In:
                            Maxim %sGorky%s. Selected short stories. Moscow: Progress Publishers,
                            1958, p. 203</biblScope></bibl>.</note>
                <note type="internal">перевод цитат и работ сомнительный</note>
